1. (A x B) ∪ {1}

First, we find the Cartesian product A x B:
A x B = {(1,3), (2,3)}

Now, we find the union with {1}:
(A x B) ∪ {1} = {(1,3), (2,3), 1}

2. A x (B ∪ {1})

First, we find the union B ∪ {1}:
B ∪ {1} = {1, 3}

Now, we find the Cartesian product A x (B ∪ {1}):
A x (B ∪ {1}) = {(1,1), (1,3), (2,1), (2,3)}

3. (A x B) ∪ ((A x {1}) ∪ (B x {1}))

First, we find the Cartesian products A x {1} and B x {1}:
A x {1} = {(1,1), (2,1)}
B x {1} = {(3,1)}

Now, we find the union (A x {1}) ∪ (B x {1}):
(A x {1}) ∪ (B x {1}) = {(1,1), (2,1), (3,1)}

Next, we find the union with (A x B):
(A x B) ∪ ((A x {1}) ∪ (B x {1})) = {(1,3), (2,3), (1,1), (2,1), (3,1)}

Now, we compare the results from (1) and (2):

(A x B) ∪ {1} = {(1,3), (2,3), 1}
A x (B ∪ {1}) = {(1,1), (1,3), (2,1), (2,3)}

Since (A x B) ∪ {1} ≠ A x (B ∪ {1}), this demonstrates that the Cartesian product of two sets is not associative with respect to union.
